## TASK
Produce a COMPLETE, READY-TO-PASTE CV (all standard sections: header, summary, skills, experience, projects, certifications, education). You may reorder or merge sections if it improves impact for data analytics.
## GLOBAL RULES (non-negotiable)
1. ACCURACY: Do not invent employers, dates, job titles, tools, metrics, degrees, or certifications. If I did not state a fact, do not add it. Use “[TBD]” or omit rather than guess.
2. NO FAKE ANALYST HISTORY: Do not imply I was employed as a “Data Analyst” unless I explicitly say so. If I am pivoting from software development, say so clearly in the summary (e.g. “technical background + strong SQL/reporting + analytics training”).
3. LINE-BY-LINE REVIEW: Treat this as an audit. For every line you output, it must be either (a) directly supported by what I provided, or (b) honest repositioning of the same facts (stronger verbs, clearer outcomes) without new false facts.
4. DATA ANALYTICS REQUIREMENTS AWARENESS: Align the CV with what DA employers typically look for, using ONLY evidence I can support:
   - SQL (querying, joins, aggregates, basic modeling via apps/projects counts if honest)
   - Spreadsheets / Excel for analysis and reporting (include Power Query / pivots ONLY if I have that experience or coursework)
   - Data cleaning, reporting, metrics, stakeholder communication (map from client work, documentation, CRUD systems)
   - Visualization / BI tools (Power BI, Tableau, Looker) ONLY if I list them; otherwise do not add as “proficient”
   - Python (pandas) ONLY at the level I specify (coursework / projects / work). If weak, say “building” or list under coursework/projects, not as multi-year job skill unless true
5. NO USELESS FILLER: Remove or shorten stack items that hurt focus for THIS application (e.g. old frameworks) unless the job posting requires them. No buzzword dumps.
6. KEYWORDS: Mirror important phrases from the job description I paste below WHERE they match my real background. Do not keyword-stuff unrelated terms.
7. METRICS: Prefer quantified bullets only when I provide numbers; otherwise use qualitative impact (e.g. “automated recurring reporting workflow”) without inventing percentages.
8. FORMAT: Clear section headings, consistent date style, parallel bullet structure, scannable in 30 seconds.
## HOW TO MAKE THE CV “STRONG” FOR DATA ANALYTICS (apply throughout)
- Lead the SUMMARY with: analytical problem-solving + SQL + structured data + reporting + communication, then secondary line on software/CAD as differentiator.
- SKILLS: Group as “Data & analytics”, “SQL & databases”, “Reporting”, then “Engineering/software” so recruiters see DA fit first.
- EXPERIENCE: Reframe bullets to emphasize: data handling, reporting outputs, automation that reduces manual data work, client/stakeholder requirements, documentation, reliability — without renaming my job falsely.
- PROJECTS: Prioritize projects with SQL, exports, CSV, dashboards (if any), or clear “data pipeline” narrative. Deprioritize or one-line irrelevant projects.
- GAPS: If there is a career gap, use neutral dates; do not fabricate employment. Optional one-line “Professional development / relocation” ONLY if I confirm it.
